          "body": "The chapter's second movement paints the terror in vivid strokes before offering any comfort. Men gripping their loins like women in labor (30:6), faces gone pale — the imagery is of total physical and psychological collapse. This is 'the time of Jacob's distress' (30:7), a phrase that has generated enormous interpretive debate. Many Reformed and evangelical scholars (Charles Feinberg, John Walvoord) identify this with the eschatological tribulation of Daniel 12:1 and Revelation 7-8, noting that the phrase 'there is none like it' is identical to Daniel's 'a time of distress such as never occurred' and Jesus's 'great tribulation such as has not occurred since the beginning of the world' (Matthew 24:21). Others (John Bright, Patrick Kelley) see the primary reference as the Babylonian conquest with secondary eschatological resonance. Both horizons are hermeneutically defensible; the near-far structure of Hebrew prophecy permits both without contradiction. What neither view disputes is the pivot of verse 7b: 'but he will be saved from it.' The salvation does not come before the distress — it comes out of it, through God's direct intervention. Verses 8-9 specify the deliverance: the yoke broken, bonds torn off, strangers no longer enslaving — and the servant people free to serve the LORD their God and 'David their king, whom I will raise up for them' (30:9). This 'David' is unmistakably messianic — the historical David died four centuries before Jeremiah wrote. Ezekiel uses identical language in 37:24-25, and the combination of Davidic royal imagery with the priestly-access language of 30:21 points definitively toward the one figure who is both King and Priest. Verses 10-11 close with the twin commands 'fear not' and 'do not be dismayed' — commands grounded not in the circumstances but in 'For I am with you' (30:11)."
