          "title": "The wound God gave and the healing only God can give (30:12-17)",
          "body": "This is the theological heart of the chapter and one of the most searching passages in the entire prophetic corpus. The wound is incurable — the Hebrew *anash* is the same word used in Jeremiah 17:9 for the desperately sick human heart. No one can plead Israel's case; no human physician has a remedy; no recovery is possible (30:12-13). The 'lovers' — the political alliances with Egypt and the surrounding nations in which Israel had trusted — have forgotten her entirely (30:14). Then comes the chapter's most bracing theological statement: 'I have wounded you with the wound of an enemy, with the punishment of a cruel one, because your iniquity is great and your sins are numerous' (30:14). God names Himself as the one who inflicted the wound. This is not Babylon acting autonomously; Babylon is the instrument; the LORD is the agent. The suffering of exile is not divine indifference or defeat — it is divine surgery. The repetition of 'your iniquity is great and your sins are numerous' in both verse 14 and verse 15 forces the moral diagnosis to be heard twice. The wound is deserved. There is no minimizing it. But then comes the astonishing turn of verse 16-17. 'Therefore' — because they are being devoured, plundered, preyed upon — God reverses the predators (30:16). And then the direct promise: 'I will restore you to health and I will heal you of your wounds' (30:17). The same God who wounded with the severity of an enemy heals with the tenderness of a father. The incurable wound — beyond every human healer — yields to the divine physician. John Calvin comments that this pattern (God wounding before healing) is the invariable structure of genuine grace: 'He does not bind up the wound until He has first exposed it.' The rationale given in verse 17 is remarkable: God heals not because Israel has repented adequately, but because 'they have called you an outcast, saying: it is Zion; no one cares for her.' The scorn of the nations, not Israel's merit, moves God's compassion."
