          "title": "The full portrait of restoration — city, congregation, covenant (30:18-22)",
          "body": "Having established the healing, the chapter opens into an extended portrait of what restoration looks like on the ground. It is comprehensively material and spiritual. The tents of Jacob will have their fortunes restored; God will have compassion on the dwelling places (30:18) — this is the intimate, domestic level. The city will be rebuilt on its ruin and the palace on its rightful place (30:18) — this is the urban, political level. Thanksgiving and celebration will replace the silence of exile; the population will multiply rather than diminish; honor will replace insignificance (30:19). The children will be 'as formerly' — a restoration that recovers the original design (30:20). The congregation will be established before God — worship and assembly reconstituted (30:20). Then comes verse 21, the chapter's most theologically concentrated verse: 'Their leader shall be one of them, and their ruler shall come forth from their midst; and I will bring him near and he shall approach Me; for who would dare to risk his life to approach Me?' The leader is native, insider, not a foreign conqueror. Two words describe his access: *qarav* (I will bring him near) and *nagash* (he will approach Me) — the second is specifically the verb used of priests approaching the altar. The rhetorical question 'who would dare to risk his life to approach Me?' is the chapter's clearest pointer toward the Messiah as the unique mediator. In the Old Testament economy, only the high priest entered the Most Holy Place, and improperly doing so meant death (Leviticus 16). This ruler's access is both granted by God and apparently unrestricted — identifying him as the one who perfectly fulfills both the Davidic royal and the Aaronic priestly offices. The chapter's destination is the covenant formula of verse 22: 'You shall be My people, and I will be your God.' This is the oldest covenant language in Scripture (Exodus 6:7; Leviticus 26:12; Jeremiah 7:23; 11:4; 31:1, 33). The entire architecture of judgment, exile, wound, healing, and restoration has been moving toward this single sentence — the relationship between God and His people, unbroken, unqualified, fully restored."
