          "body": "The chapter closes not with a soft pastoral word but with a description of divine wrath that will not turn back until it has accomplished the full intent of God's heart (30:23-24). These two verses appear almost verbatim in Jeremiah 23:19-20. Their placement here, after the restoration portrait, is deliberately reassuring rather than threatening: the same fierce wrath that falls on the wicked is the engine that drives the restorative purposes to completion. The 'intent of His heart' (*mezimmah lev*) will be performed and accomplished — God's purposes are not contingent on human cooperation or historical accident. They are driven by the will of the One whose wrath is a sweeping tempest. The closing line — 'In the latter days you will understand this' (30:24) — is honest about the limits of present comprehension. The promises of this chapter exceed what any single historical fulfillment can contain. The Babylonian return of 538 BC was real, but the unrestricted priestly-royal access of 30:21 and the covenant formula of 30:22 in their fullness await the one whom the New Testament identifies as both Son of David and eternal High Priest (Hebrews 4:14-16; 7:24-25; Revelation 19:16). The reader of Jeremiah 30 in every generation stands between the promise written and the promise fully kept, walking by the word God commanded to be written down for exactly this reason."
